WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:09.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:21.620
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much
for coming this morning.

00:00:21.620 --> 00:00:23.760
My name is Maria Pallante.

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:26.460
I'm the United States Register
of Copyrights, and on behalf

00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:28.460
of the U.S. Copyright
Office, I want to welcome you

00:00:28.460 --> 00:00:32.590
to my favorite day of
the year, World IP Day.

00:00:32.590 --> 00:00:34.960
This year's theme as given to us

00:00:34.960 --> 00:00:37.070
by the World Intellectual
Property Organization is

00:00:37.070 --> 00:00:40.140
"Digital Creativity:
Culture Reimagined."

00:00:40.140 --> 00:00:41.250
It's a great theme.

00:00:41.250 --> 00:00:43.460
It speaks to a lot of things.

00:00:43.460 --> 00:00:44.560
It speaks to balance.

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:47.440
It speaks to collaboration,
and it speaks to the fact

00:00:47.440 --> 00:00:50.010
that the digital revolution
has changed the way

00:00:50.010 --> 00:00:52.260
that people create as well.

00:00:52.260 --> 00:00:56.800
And for the fifth year, I'm
very proud and pleased to say

00:00:56.800 --> 00:00:59.760
that we are hosting
the Copyright Alliance.

00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:02.760
Standing here with me
is Keith Kupferschmid --

00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:03.910
who will speak in a moment --

00:01:03.910 --> 00:01:06.520
who is the head of the
Copyright Alliance.

00:01:06.520 --> 00:01:09.310
And as usual, the Copyright
Alliance has brought

00:01:09.310 --> 00:01:13.490
to us just an extraordinary
lineup of creators.

00:01:13.490 --> 00:01:16.900
And we will get out of
the way as fast as we can

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:19.900
so that you can enjoy
your morning with them.

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:22.990
But, before we do that, I would
like Keith to say a few words

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:25.430
about the Copyright Alliance.

00:01:25.430 --> 00:01:28.550
&gt;&gt; Well, good morning,
everybody.

00:01:28.550 --> 00:01:30.760
It's also one of my
favorite days of the year.

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:32.740
My son happens to be
born on this day as well,

00:01:32.740 --> 00:01:34.470
so that has something
to do with it.

00:01:34.470 --> 00:01:37.710
So I am the new CEO of
the Copyright Alliance.

00:01:37.710 --> 00:01:40.950
Since the Copyright Alliance has
joined in the Copyright Office

00:01:40.950 --> 00:01:44.530
in this event for the past five
years, many of you are probably

00:01:44.530 --> 00:01:47.070
at least a little bit
familiar with Alliance,

00:01:47.070 --> 00:01:50.710
but let me describe a little bit
of what we do and who we are.

00:01:50.710 --> 00:01:54.860
We represent over 15,000
individual creators

00:01:54.860 --> 00:01:58.160
and organizations from all
different copyright disciplines,

00:01:58.160 --> 00:02:01.630
from movies, music,
literary works, software,

00:02:01.630 --> 00:02:04.770
photography, the
arts, and so on.

00:02:04.770 --> 00:02:08.850
Our objective is to promote
and preserve the copyright law

00:02:08.850 --> 00:02:13.020
and to protect creators so that
they can do what they do best,

00:02:13.020 --> 00:02:15.000
which is to create.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.430
It's a pleasure to be back
here at the Copyright Office

00:02:17.430 --> 00:02:20.450
where I worked as a Policy
Planning Advisor many,

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:22.650
many, many years ago.

00:02:22.650 --> 00:02:26.780
Back then, I can recall being
very impressed by the commitment

00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:30.060
and passion of the
Copyright Office staff.

00:02:30.060 --> 00:02:32.860
As I returned to the Office
in a different capacity,

00:02:32.860 --> 00:02:34.200
it's apparent that
this commitment

00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:37.720
and dedication continues
to be the case today.

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:40.800
The copyright community is very,
very fortunate to have an office

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:42.530
that is staffed with
such devoted

00:02:42.530 --> 00:02:46.150
and enthusiastic workforce
headed by the great leadership

00:02:46.150 --> 00:02:49.930
of Register Pallante and
her legal and policy team,

00:02:49.930 --> 00:02:52.530
who I see sort of scattered
about the audience here.

00:02:52.530 --> 00:02:54.970
So, of course, it goes
without saying that we

00:02:54.970 --> 00:02:57.210
at the Copyright
Alliance are thrilled

00:02:57.210 --> 00:02:58.630
to be joining the
Copyright Office

00:02:58.630 --> 00:03:01.520
in putting together what
will be a fantastic event.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:02.280
Trust me on this one.

00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:03.950
It's going to be fantastic.

00:03:03.950 --> 00:03:05.920
And now, another thing you
should know about me is

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:07.630
that I have no creative talent.

00:03:07.630 --> 00:03:08.650
I can't sing.

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:10.010
I can't play an instrument.

00:03:10.010 --> 00:03:12.410
I can't act, and I
certainly don't code.

00:03:12.410 --> 00:03:15.140
And my idea of creative
writing is putting a contraction

00:03:15.140 --> 00:03:16.610
in a legal brief.

00:03:16.610 --> 00:03:19.160
So I consider myself
very fortunate

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:22.950
to be working alongside
and for thousands

00:03:22.950 --> 00:03:26.900
of very unbelievably talented
people, individual performers,

00:03:26.900 --> 00:03:30.230
video game developers,
photographers, songwriters,

00:03:30.230 --> 00:03:31.700
artists, directors, authors,

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:33.690
journalists, and
the list goes on.

00:03:33.690 --> 00:03:36.670
And that list includes
today's panelists.

00:03:36.670 --> 00:03:37.720
The group of the panelists

00:03:37.720 --> 00:03:40.960
that we have here today are
truly the poster children

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:43.280
for creativity and innovation.

00:03:43.280 --> 00:03:46.080
On Capitol Hill,
the press and others

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:47.820
like to pit the copyright
community

00:03:47.820 --> 00:03:50.040
against the tech community.

00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:51.020
Like the Game of Thrones,

00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:53.700
this makes for a very
compelling story,

00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:56.720
but really has no
basis in reality.

00:03:56.720 --> 00:03:59.570
The creative community is
partners and collaborators

00:03:59.570 --> 00:04:01.700
with the technology community.

00:04:01.700 --> 00:04:03.990
In many instances,
individual creators

00:04:03.990 --> 00:04:07.720
and organizations are playing
dual roles, both as creators

00:04:07.720 --> 00:04:11.140
of copyrighted works and
as technology innovators

00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:14.690
who themselves develop new
technologies or who adopt

00:04:14.690 --> 00:04:18.580
and drive demand for
technologies necessary

00:04:18.580 --> 00:04:21.660
to the creation and
distribution of their works.

00:04:21.660 --> 00:04:23.370
There are no better
examples of this

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:26.080
than the panelists
we have here today.

00:04:26.080 --> 00:04:28.560
Although I don't have any
creative talents myself,

00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:30.990
as the head of the
Copyright Alliance, it is my

00:04:30.990 --> 00:04:34.570
and my staff's responsibility
to use our legal expertise

00:04:34.570 --> 00:04:37.440
to make sure these
creators can make the most

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:38.740
out of their talents.

00:04:38.740 --> 00:04:43.060
In short, my job is to make
sure creators can do their job

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:45.250
and get paid for it.

00:04:45.250 --> 00:04:47.870
I want to briefly raise
three things that we can do

00:04:47.870 --> 00:04:49.790
to help these creators.

00:04:49.790 --> 00:04:53.130
The first is to modernize
the U.S. Copyright Office.

00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:56.090
Few government offices are
more important to the growth

00:04:56.090 --> 00:04:59.900
of creativity and commercial
activity in the United States

00:04:59.900 --> 00:05:02.420
than the U.S. Copyright Office.

00:05:02.420 --> 00:05:05.240
Despite the critical nature
of the services provided

00:05:05.240 --> 00:05:07.800
by the Office, the Office
has failed to keep pace

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:10.770
with technology and
the marketplace.

00:05:10.770 --> 00:05:13.830
To be clear, this is
not the fault of past

00:05:13.830 --> 00:05:17.070
or present Registers
or the Office itself.

00:05:17.070 --> 00:05:19.340
Many of these deficiencies
are the result of years

00:05:19.340 --> 00:05:21.990
of budgetary neglect
and structural deficits

00:05:21.990 --> 00:05:25.540
that have made it impossible
for the Office to keep pace.

00:05:25.540 --> 00:05:29.190
In fact, if you look deeper into
these problems, it's evidence

00:05:29.190 --> 00:05:31.120
that many of the
challenges confronted

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:33.670
by the Office can be
traced back to the fact

00:05:33.670 --> 00:05:36.990
that the Copyright Office is
within and under the direction

00:05:36.990 --> 00:05:39.980
and supervision of the
Library of Congress.

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:43.000
The Copyright Office must be
able to rapidly adapt to ensure

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:47.640
that it can offer the tools
and resources that all users

00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:49.670
and staff of the Office demand.

00:05:49.670 --> 00:05:52.240
And the best way to ensure this
is for the Copyright Office

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:54.660
to have control over
its IT system,

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:57.690
its budget, and its staffing.

00:05:57.690 --> 00:06:00.720
Thankfully, there is a
growing groundswell of support

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:03.160
for modernization, and
the Copyright Office seems

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:04.560
to be moving in the
right direction

00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:07.250
with its recently
released IT plan

00:06:07.250 --> 00:06:09.530
that is both forward
thinking and pragmatic.

00:06:09.530 --> 00:06:14.100
To the extent we or anyone else
has concerns with that IT plan,

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:17.420
these concerns are not with
the direction of the IT plan

00:06:17.420 --> 00:06:19.950
but rather, with how
fast the Office is moving

00:06:19.950 --> 00:06:21.700
in that direction.

00:06:21.700 --> 00:06:24.210
The sooner newer, improved
systems can be employed

00:06:24.210 --> 00:06:27.200
by the Copyright Office,
the sooner the users

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:29.390
of the Office's services
can reap the benefits

00:06:29.390 --> 00:06:31.850
of IT modernization,
and we can get closer

00:06:31.850 --> 00:06:34.690
to a 21st century
Copyright Office.

00:06:34.690 --> 00:06:37.410
The second issue I'd like
to raise is the possibility

00:06:37.410 --> 00:06:39.420
of a small claims process.

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:41.450
It's an unfortunate truth today

00:06:41.450 --> 00:06:44.760
that small creators have
rights but no remedies.

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:46.730
They struggle to protect
their copyrighted works

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:47.900
from infringement.

00:06:47.900 --> 00:06:50.160
Infringement actions are
particularly troublesome

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:52.820
for visual and literary
artists because of the nature

00:06:52.820 --> 00:06:56.960
of their transactions and
the volume of their work.

00:06:56.960 --> 00:07:00.610
One reason for this problem is
the excessive litigation costs

00:07:00.610 --> 00:07:04.070
required for bringing a
claim in federal court.

00:07:04.070 --> 00:07:06.100
We need to fix this.

00:07:06.100 --> 00:07:08.220
One way to do that
is for creators

00:07:08.220 --> 00:07:10.910
to bring small infringement
claims before a Copyright Office

00:07:10.910 --> 00:07:13.420
small claims tribunal,
instead of it having

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:14.470
to go to federal court.

00:07:14.470 --> 00:07:16.740
And that's something
we should make happen.

00:07:16.740 --> 00:07:21.420
The last issue, before we get to
the panel and other speakers --

00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:23.150
the last issue I'd like
to raise is commonly --

00:07:23.150 --> 00:07:27.010
what is commonly referred to
as the "all vid proposal."

00:07:27.010 --> 00:07:29.520
The all vid proposal is
a proposal by the FCC

00:07:29.520 --> 00:07:33.060
that will require cable and
satellite TV distributors

00:07:33.060 --> 00:07:35.420
to allow third parties
to provide subscribers

00:07:35.420 --> 00:07:37.720
with their own set
top box through which

00:07:37.720 --> 00:07:40.960
to access the TV programming
that is licensed to the --

00:07:40.960 --> 00:07:43.880
by the TV distributor.

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:47.560
While this might sound
innocuous and even laudatory,

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:50.650
the all vid proposal does not
merely allow third parties

00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:55.320
to sell TV subscribers a
cheaper or better set top box.

00:07:55.320 --> 00:07:58.970
What it does is allow that third
party, who has not paid a dime

00:07:58.970 --> 00:08:02.040
to license the copyrighted
TV programming,

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:04.900
to offer their own
commercial video service

00:08:04.900 --> 00:08:07.100
that includes that programming.

00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:10.180
In other words, the all vid
proposal will create a class

00:08:10.180 --> 00:08:13.770
of free riders that don't
have to pay for TV programming

00:08:13.770 --> 00:08:16.610
but are allowed to
make money from it.

00:08:16.610 --> 00:08:18.500
The primary form of compensation

00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:20.060
for creative professionals
responsible

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:23.000
for the video content --
the directors, the writers,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.670
the designers, the actors,
composers, costume makers,

00:08:26.670 --> 00:08:29.800
visual effect specialists,
film crews composed of grips

00:08:29.800 --> 00:08:33.590
and cameramen -- they're all
governed by complex contractual

00:08:33.590 --> 00:08:36.260
or collective bargaining
agreements that provide

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:39.350
for residuals, participation
rights,

00:08:39.350 --> 00:08:42.950
or contributions toward
health and pension benefits.

00:08:42.950 --> 00:08:46.350
By allowing the distribution
and public performance of video

00:08:46.350 --> 00:08:49.860
and entertainment works
outside of these agreements,

00:08:49.860 --> 00:08:51.770
the FCC is undermining
the system

00:08:51.770 --> 00:08:54.030
by which creators
are compensated

00:08:54.030 --> 00:08:56.900
and harming the very people
responsible for the works

00:08:56.900 --> 00:08:59.550
that consumers want to watch.

00:08:59.550 --> 00:09:02.340
While the Copyright Alliance
encourages the development

00:09:02.340 --> 00:09:05.510
of new technologies to bring
licensed works to the public

00:09:05.510 --> 00:09:09.020
in new and innovative ways,
we are gravely concerned

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:11.580
that the FCC's proposal
will permanently

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:14.720
and significantly harm these
creative professionals.

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:16.230
And so with that, you've
heard enough from me.

00:09:16.230 --> 00:09:18.180
I will turn things
over to Maria.

00:09:18.180 --> 00:09:19.510
Thank you.

00:09:19.510 --> 00:09:27.080
[ Applause ]

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:28.020
&gt;&gt; Thank you, Keith.

00:09:28.020 --> 00:09:30.910
Thank you for not saying
anything controversial.

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:37.620
World IP Day, of course,
doesn't come together in a --

00:09:37.620 --> 00:09:41.040
with a wave of a magic wand.

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:44.480
So I want to thank a few people,
if you could raise your hand.

00:09:44.480 --> 00:09:48.290
From the Copyright Alliance:
Sarah, Eileen and Claudia.

00:09:48.290 --> 00:09:51.960
And from my team:
Syreeta Swann - so shy.

00:09:51.960 --> 00:09:54.950
Syreeta is in the very back.

00:09:54.950 --> 00:09:56.450
So thank you.

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:02.290
Thank you, guys.

00:10:02.290 --> 00:10:05.080
In putting this event together,
I also want to thank those

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:06.070
of you who are

00:10:06.070 --> 00:10:10.580
from organizations also putting
together IP events today,

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:12.770
and also, we're very
sensitive to the fact that many

00:10:12.770 --> 00:10:15.290
of you are running
from event to event.

00:10:15.290 --> 00:10:19.360
We tried very hard to
schedule our event at a time

00:10:19.360 --> 00:10:21.070
that would not conflict
with other events.

00:10:21.070 --> 00:10:23.390
We weren't entirely
successful there,

00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:26.400
in part because of Chairman
Goodlatte's schedule,

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:28.250
in part because of the flights

00:10:28.250 --> 00:10:31.790
of our extraordinary
artistic talent that has come

00:10:31.790 --> 00:10:34.420
into D.C. today to be with you.

00:10:34.420 --> 00:10:39.600
So, as it turns out, Chairman
Goodlatte has pre-recorded his

00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:43.420
remarks today so that we could
hold this event in the morning

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:46.290
to make sure that we had all
of our artistic team here.

00:10:46.290 --> 00:10:49.530
And I'll introduce
him in a moment.

00:10:49.530 --> 00:10:53.820
What I wanted to say,
though, is that if you go back

00:10:53.820 --> 00:10:56.730
to Copyright Review three years
ago, you know that the advice

00:10:56.730 --> 00:10:59.320
of the Copyright
Office to Congress was

00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:02.580
that the time had come for them
to step back and look at all

00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:05.260
of the different
issues that a variety

00:11:05.260 --> 00:11:07.010
of stakeholders were
putting forward

00:11:07.010 --> 00:11:11.610
as the singular most
important issue or, in fact,

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:14.970
the issue that Congress
should stay away from

00:11:14.970 --> 00:11:17.630
and let the marketplace handle.

00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:20.340
And our advice to
Congress was that Congress

00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:23.030
and Congress alone has
the role constitutionally

00:11:23.030 --> 00:11:26.080
of balancing all of those public
equities and stepping back

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:31.190
and then deciding whether to
act or whether to revise the law

00:11:31.190 --> 00:11:33.840
or whether to monitor
marketplace developments,

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:36.650
all of which are the
domain of Congress.

00:11:36.650 --> 00:11:42.240
In making that recommendation,
we noted that in order for that

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:45.860
to happen, you need to have
committee leadership in Congress

00:11:45.860 --> 00:11:49.550
that has a meaningful degree of
fluency in the Copyright Act,

00:11:49.550 --> 00:11:54.750
as well as a staff committed
to that committee or committees

00:11:54.750 --> 00:11:57.270
that also has a meaningful
degree of fluency

00:11:57.270 --> 00:12:00.280
and a commitment to
keep copyright moving

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:03.240
from session to session.

00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:06.220
And as such, we were
absolutely pleased

00:12:06.220 --> 00:12:09.100
that Chairman Goodlatte first
put Copyright Review before the

00:12:09.100 --> 00:12:12.950
Subcommittee on Intellectual
Property and then moved it

00:12:12.950 --> 00:12:15.690
to the full committee
level, where it still is,

00:12:15.690 --> 00:12:18.900
and as we move to the
next session of Congress,

00:12:18.900 --> 00:12:23.110
I just want to make sure that we
all thank him for stepping back

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:25.570
and running such an
incredibly transparent

00:12:25.570 --> 00:12:27.740
and comprehensive process.

00:12:27.740 --> 00:12:30.480
And you're probably
wondering what's next.

00:12:30.480 --> 00:12:33.610
And I think you'll find that
in his recorded remarks,

00:12:33.610 --> 00:12:35.560
he answers that question.

00:12:35.560 --> 00:12:48.000
So although he's not here,
let me introduce him.

00:12:51.720 --> 00:12:53.240
Some things you may
not know about him.

00:12:53.240 --> 00:12:54.730
So you know that
he is the Chairman

00:12:54.730 --> 00:12:56.740
of the House Judiciary
Committee.

00:12:56.740 --> 00:13:00.070
How many of you knew that he is
the first Judiciary Committee

00:13:00.070 --> 00:13:04.620
Chairman from Virginia
in the last 125 years?

00:13:04.620 --> 00:13:07.150
Raise your hand if
you knew that.

00:13:07.150 --> 00:13:09.130
That's an extraordinary fact.

00:13:09.130 --> 00:13:11.310
The House Judiciary
Committee, aside from looking

00:13:11.310 --> 00:13:13.410
at copyright law, is at
the forefront of some

00:13:13.410 --> 00:13:15.850
of the most significant
issues of the day,

00:13:15.850 --> 00:13:17.910
including protecting
constitutional freedoms

00:13:17.910 --> 00:13:20.520
and civil liberties, oversight
of the U.S. Departments

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:23.660
of Justice and Homeland
Security, legal and regulatory,

00:13:23.660 --> 00:13:26.140
[inaudible] innovation,
competition and antitrust laws,

00:13:26.140 --> 00:13:28.750
terrorism, crime,
and immigration.

00:13:28.750 --> 00:13:32.110
Many of these issues will
be the deciding factors

00:13:32.110 --> 00:13:34.590
in determining the future
direction of our nation.

00:13:34.590 --> 00:13:35.280
The jurisdiction

00:13:35.280 --> 00:13:37.490
of the Judiciary Committee
is well suited to many

00:13:37.490 --> 00:13:40.550
of Bob's legislative
priorities, which are IP,

00:13:40.550 --> 00:13:43.440
constitutional rights,
private property,

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:45.680
Second Amendment rights,
securing our borders,

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:50.370
strengthening our criminal
laws, and so forth.

00:13:50.370 --> 00:13:53.010
We are indebted, of course,
in the copyright community

00:13:53.010 --> 00:13:57.910
for his very forward thinking
and thoughtful leadership,

00:13:57.910 --> 00:14:00.840
and without further ado, I'd
like to introduce, virtually,

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:03.640
Bob Goodlatte, Chairman of
the House Judiciary Committee.

00:14:03.640 --> 00:14:08.180
&gt;&gt; Thanks for the opportunity to
give remarks at today's event.

00:14:08.180 --> 00:14:10.350
Unfortunately, I had a
preexisting commitment

00:14:10.350 --> 00:14:12.790
in Charlottesville this
morning that prevented me

00:14:12.790 --> 00:14:14.730
from being with you in person.

00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:16.850
Three years ago, the
Committee began a process

00:14:16.850 --> 00:14:19.790
to thoroughly review our
nation's copyright law,

00:14:19.790 --> 00:14:23.140
an overdue effort that
resulted in gathering input

00:14:23.140 --> 00:14:26.630
from a diverse range of
copyright creators, owners,

00:14:26.630 --> 00:14:29.720
distributors, platforms,
and end users.

00:14:29.720 --> 00:14:33.110
Beginning with 100 witnesses
at 20 formal hearings,

00:14:33.110 --> 00:14:36.320
the Committee then traveled
to Nashville, Santa Clara,

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:39.680
and Los Angeles for
three public roundtables

00:14:39.680 --> 00:14:41.290
with over 60 participants.

00:14:41.290 --> 00:14:44.850
Committee staff then followed
up with all prior witnesses

00:14:44.850 --> 00:14:47.320
and those who had expressed
an interest in copyright,

00:14:47.320 --> 00:14:49.290
to develop a comprehensive
record

00:14:49.290 --> 00:14:53.170
of the issues facing the
American copyright system today.

00:14:53.170 --> 00:14:55.960
What copyright issues did
the Committee hear about?

00:14:55.960 --> 00:14:58.090
More than most could imagine.

00:14:58.090 --> 00:14:59.940
Some of the topics included:

00:14:59.940 --> 00:15:03.360
In what ways can consensus be
achieved in copyright policy?

00:15:03.360 --> 00:15:04.720
How does copyright

00:15:04.720 --> 00:15:07.540
and technology create
innovation in America?

00:15:07.540 --> 00:15:10.260
What is the proper role
of voluntary agreements

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:11.630
and how can they be encouraged?

00:15:11.630 --> 00:15:14.980
Does the scope of copyright
protection need updating?

00:15:14.980 --> 00:15:18.510
Does the fair use balance,
as it exists today,

00:15:18.510 --> 00:15:22.210
reflect congressional intent
when it was first codified?

00:15:22.210 --> 00:15:26.570
Is section 512 working well
for all interested parties?

00:15:26.570 --> 00:15:30.870
Are bad faith actors abusing
the notice and takedown system?

00:15:30.870 --> 00:15:35.240
Does U.S. law create the proper
framework for the preservation

00:15:35.240 --> 00:15:39.150
and reuse of copyrighted works
that are either deteriorating

00:15:39.150 --> 00:15:41.850
or lacking copyright
ownership information?

00:15:41.850 --> 00:15:46.100
Is the current compulsory
video license framework the

00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:47.040
best approach?

00:15:47.040 --> 00:15:49.790
How is first sale
working in a world

00:15:49.790 --> 00:15:51.680
of mixed and digital goods?

00:15:51.680 --> 00:15:55.630
Does the music licensing system
work to the detriment or success

00:15:55.630 --> 00:15:58.490
of musicians, and is the
current compulsory license

00:15:58.490 --> 00:15:59.420
system working?

00:15:59.420 --> 00:16:03.190
Is the termination rights
framework too complicated?

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:08.000
Does the U.S. need greater moral
rights or a resell royalty?

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.480
Does the current remedies
framework reflect an appropriate

00:16:11.480 --> 00:16:14.920
balance between providing
compensation for damages,

00:16:14.920 --> 00:16:18.860
for actual losses, while
deterring future infringements?

00:16:18.860 --> 00:16:22.350
Does this same remedies
framework provide a meaningful

00:16:22.350 --> 00:16:26.060
enforcement right for
smaller copyright claims?

00:16:26.060 --> 00:16:28.400
Do the anti-circumvention
provisions

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:32.040
of Chapter 12 efficiently
determine exemptions

00:16:32.040 --> 00:16:35.290
for adverse effects
on non-infringing uses

00:16:35.290 --> 00:16:38.560
or for security and
encryption research?

00:16:38.560 --> 00:16:41.550
Are the needs of the visually
impaired community being met?

00:16:41.550 --> 00:16:44.920
What is the impact of current
copyright law upon students,

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:47.750
professors, and their
academic institutions?

00:16:47.750 --> 00:16:49.730
Is the Copyright
Office functioning well

00:16:49.730 --> 00:16:52.780
in its present framework, or
is there another framework

00:16:52.780 --> 00:16:54.020
that would work better?

00:16:54.020 --> 00:16:57.940
What are the resources and
information technology necessary

00:16:57.940 --> 00:17:00.270
for the Copyright
Office to function well?

00:17:00.270 --> 00:17:03.370
While not all of these questions
are of interest to everyone

00:17:03.370 --> 00:17:04.750
in the copyright system,

00:17:04.750 --> 00:17:07.470
they demonstrate the
interconnected nature

00:17:07.470 --> 00:17:09.530
of U.S. copyright law.

00:17:09.530 --> 00:17:12.820
Simply changing a paragraph
here and a word or two there

00:17:12.820 --> 00:17:16.670
in Title 17 may have a
major impact far beyond its

00:17:16.670 --> 00:17:18.100
intended approach.

00:17:18.100 --> 00:17:19.360
Thus, it is critical

00:17:19.360 --> 00:17:23.160
that Congress understand the
overall impact of any changes

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:25.400
in copyright law
before proceeding

00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:27.810
with formally introduced
legislation.

00:17:27.810 --> 00:17:32.040
It is also clear that neither a
solely copyright owner-focused

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:35.520
bill nor a copyright
user-focused bill could be

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:38.780
enacted by Congress
today nor should they be.

00:17:38.780 --> 00:17:40.200
Any potential changes

00:17:40.200 --> 00:17:43.900
to copyright law cannot be
based upon mere talking points

00:17:43.900 --> 00:17:45.310
of interested parties.

00:17:45.310 --> 00:17:48.250
Copyright law, much like
all of the other titles

00:17:48.250 --> 00:17:50.820
of the U.S. Code, are
about the details.

00:17:50.820 --> 00:17:53.430
Words matter, not bullet points.

00:17:53.430 --> 00:17:56.220
In the weeks ahead,
we will identify areas

00:17:56.220 --> 00:17:59.380
where there is a likelihood,
a potential consensus,

00:17:59.380 --> 00:18:00.760
and circulate outlines

00:18:00.760 --> 00:18:03.200
of potential reforms
in those areas.

00:18:03.200 --> 00:18:06.190
Then, we will convene
stakeholders for further work

00:18:06.190 --> 00:18:08.280
on these potential reforms.

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:10.260
And you have my personal
commitment

00:18:10.260 --> 00:18:12.930
that as the review shifts
to more focused work

00:18:12.930 --> 00:18:16.060
on potential reforms, the
process will be transparent,

00:18:16.060 --> 00:18:18.180
and the Committee will
continue to ensure

00:18:18.180 --> 00:18:21.710
that all interested parties
have the opportunity to weigh

00:18:21.710 --> 00:18:23.610
in on issues of concern to them.

00:18:23.610 --> 00:18:26.950
Our copyright system
deserves no less.

00:18:26.950 --> 00:18:28.410
While no one can guarantee

00:18:28.410 --> 00:18:31.510
that every interested party
will share the same views

00:18:31.510 --> 00:18:35.040
on every copyright policy
issue, I can guarantee

00:18:35.040 --> 00:18:37.940
that we will have an open
ear to everyone who wants

00:18:37.940 --> 00:18:39.890
to contribute to this process.

00:18:39.890 --> 00:18:41.520
All views are welcome.

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:43.120
Thank you again for
the opportunity

00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:44.660
to speak with you today.

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:47.330
When our nation's founders
included intellectual property

00:18:47.330 --> 00:18:50.340
in our constitution, they
recognized the importance

00:18:50.340 --> 00:18:53.470
of creativity to our
nation and our economy.

00:18:53.470 --> 00:18:57.500
We need to ensure that our laws
continue to promote creativity

00:18:57.500 --> 00:18:59.830
and innovation in
the digital age.

00:18:59.830 --> 00:19:07.850
I look forward to working
with you in the months ahead.

00:19:07.850 --> 00:19:08.150
&gt;&gt; All right.

00:19:08.150 --> 00:19:10.970
So you've heard from
all of us policy

