&gt;&gt; Great. Jared, what
brought you to the arts?

00:53:21.530 --> 00:53:25.870
&gt;&gt; I was really fortunate
enough to grow up in New York,

00:53:25.870 --> 00:53:31.800
and my parents took me to live
Broadway shows when I was a kid.

00:53:31.800 --> 00:53:36.210
And being in the audience
and being in the same room

00:53:36.210 --> 00:53:39.260
with the audience and the
performers at the same time

00:53:39.260 --> 00:53:42.820
and feeling what they're
feeling at the same time,

00:53:42.820 --> 00:53:46.560
it felt like I was a part
of it, because I felt

00:53:46.560 --> 00:53:50.320
like if I wasn't here, maybe the
performance would be different.

00:53:50.320 --> 00:53:55.580
And so from the very early age
I wanted to always be a part

00:53:55.580 --> 00:54:02.070
of that feeling, being a
part of sharing ideas and art

00:54:02.070 --> 00:54:05.220
in such a visceral
and immediate way.

00:54:05.220 --> 00:54:09.950
And I started working
out in theater.

00:54:09.950 --> 00:54:13.640
I worked off Broadway
shows as a --

00:54:13.640 --> 00:54:17.260
doing anything that I could
do just to be a part of it.

00:54:17.260 --> 00:54:21.380
And I worked as a P.A.,
and then a stage manager,

00:54:21.380 --> 00:54:24.730
and then I just started
producing my own shows,

00:54:24.730 --> 00:54:29.900
and so yeah, and I think that
actually having a background

00:54:29.900 --> 00:54:33.730
with live and experiencing
things live

00:54:33.730 --> 00:54:36.780
and immediately really
speaks to what we're talking

00:54:36.780 --> 00:54:40.240
about here today with
the digital format

00:54:40.240 --> 00:54:42.430
because what we do,
like Chase said,

00:54:42.430 --> 00:54:45.480
he's going to push this out,
something that we made together

00:54:45.480 --> 00:54:49.090
to two million people,
and that's exciting.

00:54:49.090 --> 00:54:55.180
And the fact that we can share
that together is inspiring

00:54:55.180 --> 00:54:56.810
and really exciting to me.

00:54:56.810 --> 00:54:59.380
&gt;&gt; Great. So the rest of
my questions are aimed

00:54:59.380 --> 00:55:02.920
at one particular person, but
if the other panelists want

00:55:02.920 --> 00:55:05.030
to jump in, feel free.

00:55:05.030 --> 00:55:07.420
So, Chase, I'm going
to start with you.

00:55:07.420 --> 00:55:11.260
You created an online classroom,
bringing together creators

00:55:11.260 --> 00:55:14.420
with the world's top
experts in their fields.

00:55:14.420 --> 00:55:17.540
And what is it about the current
creative economy that led you

00:55:17.540 --> 00:55:20.340
to develop this dynamic website?

00:55:20.340 --> 00:55:20.760
&gt;&gt; Oh, man.

00:55:20.760 --> 00:55:24.460
There's a -- it's a
convergence of many things.

00:55:24.460 --> 00:55:27.750
I like the question
because it addresses a --

00:55:27.750 --> 00:55:33.160
what I think that is there's
a real need and a vacancy,

00:55:33.160 --> 00:55:36.320
that we value creativity.

00:55:36.320 --> 00:55:39.990
Look at all of the
industry around creativity.

00:55:39.990 --> 00:55:41.000
As I mentioned earlier,

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:44.060
everything in your
world was designed.

00:55:44.060 --> 00:55:45.160
It was first concepted

00:55:45.160 --> 00:55:48.700
by an artist before
it was manufactured.

00:55:48.700 --> 00:55:51.000
And there's a real
disconnect between --

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:54.300
we throw around words like
innovation and creativity,

00:55:54.300 --> 00:55:55.860
but we don't know
what that means,

00:55:55.860 --> 00:55:57.130
and we don't know
where it comes from.

00:55:57.130 --> 00:56:00.650
Well, it comes from
fostering and nurturing that.

00:56:00.650 --> 00:56:05.860
And we can't have a culture
that values it, but a system

00:56:05.860 --> 00:56:08.470
that doesn't provide for
it, which is currently --

00:56:08.470 --> 00:56:12.130
the education system is very,
very broken in our country.

00:56:12.130 --> 00:56:16.520
One of the first things to
get cut, the arts programs.

00:56:16.520 --> 00:56:20.480
And so, I recognize
that, and with a bunch --

00:56:20.480 --> 00:56:23.130
to be crystal clear, it's myself
plus it's a hundred other people

00:56:23.130 --> 00:56:25.920
who go to work at CreativeLive
every day with the vision

00:56:25.920 --> 00:56:28.620
of helping people
live that life.

00:56:28.620 --> 00:56:33.650
And there's another disconnect
around sort of the ability

00:56:33.650 --> 00:56:36.420
to make a living and
a life as a creative.

00:56:36.420 --> 00:56:38.640
We talked about this
last night at the bar.

00:56:38.640 --> 00:56:43.000
I don't know if I'm
supposed to say that.

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:47.160
And it's -- art school
currently does not create --

00:56:47.160 --> 00:56:50.560
there's no part of the
curricula that has anything

00:56:50.560 --> 00:56:52.400
to do with the business.

00:56:52.400 --> 00:56:56.170
And so at CreativeLive, we
wanted to connect millions

00:56:56.170 --> 00:56:58.350
of creators all over the
world who are interested --

00:56:58.350 --> 00:57:00.330
and these are people who
are going not just from one

00:57:00.330 --> 00:57:01.300
to ten in their career.

00:57:01.300 --> 00:57:03.110
They're already identified
as a creative,

00:57:03.110 --> 00:57:04.950
and they're becoming
more creative,

00:57:04.950 --> 00:57:07.660
or they're having a
more successful career,

00:57:07.660 --> 00:57:10.520
but these are also people who
are going from zero to one.

00:57:10.520 --> 00:57:13.240
These are people who
are working at Amazon

00:57:13.240 --> 00:57:15.570
or in an accounting firm,

00:57:15.570 --> 00:57:16.850
and they've been
told their whole life

00:57:16.850 --> 00:57:17.560
that they weren't creative.

00:57:17.560 --> 00:57:18.720
My Mom is a great example.

00:57:18.720 --> 00:57:20.680
Told her whole life
she wasn't creative

00:57:20.680 --> 00:57:22.610
and then I gave her an iPhone,

00:57:22.610 --> 00:57:24.880
and with that little
app I created in 2009,

00:57:24.880 --> 00:57:28.000
and she went instantly from
being not recognized as creative

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:30.490
to the most creative
of all her friends.

00:57:30.490 --> 00:57:32.910
"Joy, your pictures
are incredible."

00:57:32.910 --> 00:57:37.250
Now, those two communities
are both underserved.

00:57:37.250 --> 00:57:41.300
So by creating CreativeLive,
we were hoping to sort

00:57:41.300 --> 00:57:44.110
of support that, support the
areas, the gaps in our culture

00:57:44.110 --> 00:57:47.460
that were missing at this
point, and teach them how

00:57:47.460 --> 00:57:49.880
to make a living and
a life from people

00:57:49.880 --> 00:57:51.210
who are actually doing it.

00:57:51.210 --> 00:57:53.820
This is not an academic
institution.

00:57:53.820 --> 00:57:57.570
It is very much a practical,
hands-on, skill-based learning.

00:57:57.570 --> 00:58:00.750
And when you have instructors,
who are world-class experts,

00:58:00.750 --> 00:58:02.590
and I'm talking -- I mean,
you saw the list of names:

00:58:02.590 --> 00:58:05.340
Pulitzer Prize winners, New
York Times best-selling authors,

00:58:05.340 --> 00:58:07.540
Grammy award winners,
Oscar award winners.

00:58:07.540 --> 00:58:08.830
These are people
that are coming back

00:58:08.830 --> 00:58:10.190
and giving back to
their community.

00:58:10.190 --> 00:58:13.590
They're also getting
compensated, but to me,

00:58:13.590 --> 00:58:16.110
that's a gap in the
sort of marketplace

00:58:16.110 --> 00:58:22.940
and intellectual cultural
space that we needed to fill.

00:58:22.940 --> 00:58:24.610
&gt;&gt; Great, thank you.

00:58:24.610 --> 00:58:25.720
Jared, some other questions.

00:58:25.720 --> 00:58:27.850
So what first sparked
your decision

00:58:27.850 --> 00:58:31.690
to explore online collaboration
and use digital tools

00:58:31.690 --> 00:58:35.470
to create and distribute works?

00:58:35.470 --> 00:58:36.520
&gt;&gt; It's funny.

00:58:36.520 --> 00:58:40.900
There was no decision really.

00:58:40.900 --> 00:58:44.230
This was something that,
especially for me, well, for me,

00:58:44.230 --> 00:58:45.420
personally, was something

00:58:45.420 --> 00:58:48.730
that just happened
pretty organically.

00:58:48.730 --> 00:58:54.320
Like I said, I have a background
in live shows and live art.

00:58:54.320 --> 00:58:58.500
And I had worked on a play
with Joe Gordon-Levitt.

00:58:58.500 --> 00:59:03.370
And I think it was about ten
years ago, he put this --

00:59:03.370 --> 00:59:04.660
this is before YouTube.

00:59:04.660 --> 00:59:07.440
So, I guess, it was
more like 11 years ago.

00:59:07.440 --> 00:59:11.390
He put up an online
journal called HITRECORD

00:59:11.390 --> 00:59:15.120
where he thought, "A lot of
people know me as an actor,

00:59:15.120 --> 00:59:16.190
but they don't know
me as a writer.

00:59:16.190 --> 00:59:17.870
They don't know me
as a musician."

00:59:17.870 --> 00:59:22.160
And so he put up a journal,
a blog that would --

00:59:22.160 --> 00:59:26.670
he would put up writing, and he
would put up video and music,

00:59:26.670 --> 00:59:28.170
and people would download it.

00:59:28.170 --> 00:59:30.600
This is before click-to-play
video.

00:59:30.600 --> 00:59:34.030
And a community started
to crop up.

00:59:34.030 --> 00:59:38.520
People were writing to him what
they thought about his art,

00:59:38.520 --> 00:59:41.560
and then it became a little
bit more of a dialogue,

00:59:41.560 --> 00:59:45.590
and Joe would respond to
what people were saying.

00:59:45.590 --> 00:59:50.330
And then I remember he made a
very crucial decision as to:

00:59:50.330 --> 00:59:51.790
do we put up a message board?

00:59:51.790 --> 00:59:57.150
Do we put up a message board so
people can talk more, faster,

00:59:57.150 --> 01:00:02.040
and the dialogue can
just get more specific?

01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:05.710
And it was a big decision, and
he put up this message board.

01:00:05.710 --> 01:00:11.800
And what we -- what started
happening almost instantaneously

01:00:11.800 --> 01:00:15.070
was not, "Hey, I'm going
to put this thing up,

01:00:15.070 --> 01:00:16.500
and then you respond to it."

01:00:16.500 --> 01:00:19.200
It was -- there was a natural
progression that people wanted

01:00:19.200 --> 01:00:21.790
to start creating together.

01:00:21.790 --> 01:00:26.060
And on this message board
with just a few hundred people

01:00:26.060 --> 01:00:30.400
at the start, the very first
collaboration that we had

01:00:30.400 --> 01:00:33.980
or that was up on the message
board was a word association

01:00:33.980 --> 01:00:35.800
game where somebody
would say a word

01:00:35.800 --> 01:00:37.600
and then another person
would say the first thing

01:00:37.600 --> 01:00:39.290
that popped to mind.

01:00:39.290 --> 01:00:42.860
And then that evolved into
thousands and thousands

01:00:42.860 --> 01:00:44.470
of words, and then
somebody had the idea,

01:00:44.470 --> 01:00:47.340
"Let's take all these words
and make a story out of it."

01:00:47.340 --> 01:00:50.910
And so I think people
have the natural tendency

01:00:50.910 --> 01:00:52.970
to want to create together.

01:00:52.970 --> 01:00:57.430
And after more and more of
these threads with different --

01:00:57.430 --> 01:01:00.670
there was a writing
collaboration

01:01:00.670 --> 01:01:03.090
and a music collaboration
and a video collaboration --

01:01:03.090 --> 01:01:07.650
we started talking
and said, there's --

01:01:07.650 --> 01:01:09.130
people want to do this.

01:01:09.130 --> 01:01:12.180
Let's provide a --
we've got to create --

01:01:12.180 --> 01:01:14.340
we're developing this
creative community

01:01:14.340 --> 01:01:17.860
and sometimes providing
some creative direction.

01:01:17.860 --> 01:01:20.830
How can we really make --

01:01:20.830 --> 01:01:27.620
turn this into something where
we're making real productions,

01:01:27.620 --> 01:01:28.890
authoring in terms of service,

01:01:28.890 --> 01:01:31.190
making it legal and
paying people?

01:01:31.190 --> 01:01:35.520
And that's what we did,
and starting in 2009,

01:01:35.520 --> 01:01:38.950
we started building
the tech infrastructure

01:01:38.950 --> 01:01:41.480
and the legal infrastructure
to do that.

01:01:41.480 --> 01:01:44.560
So, I mean, just to answer
your question more succinctly,

01:01:44.560 --> 01:01:48.010
it wasn't a decision as much as
it was a natural progression.

01:01:48.010 --> 01:01:53.790
And I think that's what makes
our community so special is

01:01:53.790 --> 01:01:57.020
that it wasn't -- it's
not a marketing campaign.

01:01:57.020 --> 01:01:59.290
It's not something
that we forced.

01:01:59.290 --> 01:02:02.620
If you were to say how do
you make an online community,

01:02:02.620 --> 01:02:05.660
I wouldn't be able to answer it.

01:02:05.660 --> 01:02:07.280
But yeah.

01:02:07.280 --> 01:02:08.740
&gt;&gt; Great, thanks.

01:02:08.740 --> 01:02:12.130
Anna, so what are some of
the challenges that you faced

01:02:12.130 --> 01:02:14.600
when trying to connect
with your audiences?

01:02:14.600 --> 01:02:16.660
People looking for
wedding gifts,

01:02:16.660 --> 01:02:18.860
but they've never
heard of Gather?

01:02:18.860 --> 01:02:22.700
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Well, I think it's
kind of a two part answer.

01:02:22.700 --> 01:02:28.610
One is it boils down to sort
of straight up marketing

01:02:28.610 --> 01:02:31.850
and the ability to just get
a product out into the world.

01:02:31.850 --> 01:02:35.980
We have lots of mechanisms
to do that.

01:02:35.980 --> 01:02:40.720
Right now, I think
the most exciting part

01:02:40.720 --> 01:02:43.430
about our business model
and the way that we do it is

01:02:43.430 --> 01:02:46.580
that there's this whole industry

01:02:46.580 --> 01:02:49.830
where people get
hitched all the time.

01:02:49.830 --> 01:02:54.910
And there's a gift economy
associated with getting married.

01:02:54.910 --> 01:02:58.660
And so when two people decide
they're going to do that,

01:02:58.660 --> 01:03:05.530
they send out our information,
as any kind of wedding registry

01:03:05.530 --> 01:03:11.630
or any kind of ecommerce
platform at this point, to 250,

01:03:11.630 --> 01:03:13.370
300 of their favorite friends.

01:03:13.370 --> 01:03:17.310
And so those people are really
doing our marketing for us,

01:03:17.310 --> 01:03:20.660
which is actually
kind of a cool thing.

01:03:20.660 --> 01:03:26.810
I think -- and so I think our
challenge is to get the interest

01:03:26.810 --> 01:03:32.350
of that original couple, the
sort of -- our original client,

01:03:32.350 --> 01:03:36.010
if you will, and one of the
things that is really exciting

01:03:36.010 --> 01:03:39.080
about that is that they
tend to be younger,

01:03:39.080 --> 01:03:40.950
and they tend to be interested.

01:03:40.950 --> 01:03:44.200
They have all of the towels and
the toasters that they need.

01:03:44.200 --> 01:03:45.870
And so they tend
to be interested

01:03:45.870 --> 01:03:51.090
in doing something unique
and so when we intersect

01:03:51.090 --> 01:03:54.690
with those couples, the
people who are interested

01:03:54.690 --> 01:03:58.610
in registering with Gather
or anybody who's interested

01:03:58.610 --> 01:04:02.100
in setting up a gift registry
for that matter, it's a matter

01:04:02.100 --> 01:04:04.510
of communication, and I
think that's the second part

01:04:04.510 --> 01:04:09.550
of it is how do we effectively
talk about value and curation?

01:04:09.550 --> 01:04:14.500
What is it that makes the artist
that we represent excellent?

01:04:14.500 --> 01:04:17.860
I think the idea of excellence
is something that we --

01:04:17.860 --> 01:04:20.110
is a conversation
that is evolving

01:04:20.110 --> 01:04:23.500
as we put our work
out into the world.

01:04:23.500 --> 01:04:26.560
How do we curate and how do
we consider different works

01:04:26.560 --> 01:04:29.040
of art to be excellent?

01:04:29.040 --> 01:04:34.410
And we really work hard on
trying to communicate that gap

01:04:34.410 --> 01:04:37.480
between what are the --

01:04:37.480 --> 01:04:43.030
I have this user experience
when I go into Macy's online.

01:04:43.030 --> 01:04:44.990
I'm going to pick on Macy's.

01:04:44.990 --> 01:04:46.840
Their online registry page.

01:04:46.840 --> 01:04:50.480
I feel like that's the kind of
user experience I want to have,

01:04:50.480 --> 01:04:52.940
and so does that --
can that translate

01:04:52.940 --> 01:04:58.240
into bringing the fine
art object to my life?

01:04:58.240 --> 01:05:01.100
And our task is to
say yes, it is.

01:05:01.100 --> 01:05:02.730
There are some things we
have to negotiate, but --

01:05:02.730 --> 01:05:07.300
and effectively communicating
those differences is really kind

01:05:07.300 --> 01:05:08.560
of our challenge.

01:05:08.560 --> 01:05:09.320
Yeah.

01:05:09.320 --> 01:05:11.140
&gt;&gt; All right, thanks.

01:05:11.140 --> 01:05:13.470
Chase, there's a lot of
talk in the arts community

01:05:13.470 --> 01:05:17.550
about finding ways to support
artist-centered technologies.

01:05:17.550 --> 01:05:20.520
What's the value in artists
developing their own online

01:05:20.520 --> 01:05:25.000
platforms to distribute
and make creative content?

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:29.640
&gt;&gt; Well, it's the first time
in the history of the world

01:05:29.640 --> 01:05:33.640
that we are not bound
by gatekeepers.

01:05:33.640 --> 01:05:37.360
We require no permission
now to share at scale.

01:05:37.360 --> 01:05:40.360
It used to be we were kept
out by the gallerists,

01:05:40.360 --> 01:05:45.720
by the photo editor,
by the art director,

01:05:45.720 --> 01:05:47.890
or the creative director
at the agency.

01:05:47.890 --> 01:05:53.900
And now with the benefits
of technology, you can reach

01:05:53.900 --> 01:05:57.490
that same scale or much greater,
as in my earlier example,

01:05:57.490 --> 01:05:58.980
at the push of a button.

01:05:58.980 --> 01:06:03.920
So what that creates is in
many ways a sense of freedom.

01:06:03.920 --> 01:06:09.180
And the technology -- the sort
of technology community --

01:06:09.180 --> 01:06:11.360
I don't want to put
crosshairs on their back.

01:06:11.360 --> 01:06:15.270
I think Joe is wise to point
out that Google and Facebook

01:06:15.270 --> 01:06:19.380
and others are making billions,
hundreds of billions of dollars.

01:06:19.380 --> 01:06:24.330
But the message isn't
that they should not exist

01:06:24.330 --> 01:06:26.800
or that we should
continue on the paradigm.

01:06:26.800 --> 01:06:31.740
It is a very, very dynamic
and complicated thing.

01:06:31.740 --> 01:06:35.330
For me, technology
literally created my career.

01:06:35.330 --> 01:06:37.200
I was a very sexy?

01:06:37.200 --> 01:06:39.160
I was a very sexy photographer.

01:06:39.160 --> 01:06:44.720
I was a very successful
photographer pre-internet

01:06:44.720 --> 01:06:48.640
because I learned the
value of my work early,

01:06:48.640 --> 01:06:50.030
and that was out of necessity.

01:06:50.030 --> 01:06:52.030
I needed to eat.

01:06:52.030 --> 01:06:53.630
I needed to put food
on the table

01:06:53.630 --> 01:06:56.490
so I'm not naturally
gifted in business.

01:06:56.490 --> 01:06:58.200
I had to become that.

01:06:58.200 --> 01:07:01.850
And I was very happy
with my career and then

01:07:01.850 --> 01:07:05.350
in a pre-YouTube -- it was
called Google Video at the time,

01:07:05.350 --> 01:07:09.230
where you could put up videos,
I started telling the story

01:07:09.230 --> 01:07:11.380
of what I call the black
box of photography.

01:07:11.380 --> 01:07:15.810
It was a very closed
world, and if you were

01:07:15.810 --> 01:07:20.120
out there sharing a point
of view, you were sort of --

01:07:20.120 --> 01:07:23.140
the industry or the people that
were comprised of the leaders

01:07:23.140 --> 01:07:25.970
in the industry were
very upset with you.

01:07:25.970 --> 01:07:29.750
I was vilified, in fact,
for sharing the first videos

01:07:29.750 --> 01:07:32.060
that I was -- about what it
was like to go on location.

01:07:32.060 --> 01:07:35.350
It doesn't matter -- I
was shooting for the Nikes

01:07:35.350 --> 01:07:40.850
and the Apples and Fortune 100
brands, and telling the story

01:07:40.850 --> 01:07:45.000
about what it was like to
do that, effectively opening

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:46.530
up this sort of black box,

01:07:46.530 --> 01:07:49.660
and sharing secrets was
a very risky proposition,

01:07:49.660 --> 01:07:52.290
and you might be sitting in
the audience judging, thinking,

01:07:52.290 --> 01:07:54.060
"Well, geez, why aren't
you undermining your

01:07:54.060 --> 01:07:55.350
own livelihood?"

01:07:55.350 --> 01:07:57.510
But the reality is
that we need to --

01:07:57.510 --> 01:08:00.290
there needs to be some sort of
middle ground between pretending

01:08:00.290 --> 01:08:03.360
that that doesn't exist, a
head in the sand mentality,

01:08:03.360 --> 01:08:04.350
and acknowledging

01:08:04.350 --> 01:08:07.330
that information is moving
faster than ever before.

01:08:07.330 --> 01:08:12.330
So it was my very proactive
decision to sort of open that up

01:08:12.330 --> 01:08:14.280
and to help other
people become --

01:08:14.280 --> 01:08:17.000
I wanted to take a world of
just millions of photographers

01:08:17.000 --> 01:08:20.350
and make it into a world of
billions of photographers.

01:08:20.350 --> 01:08:24.100
And make the image more
popular than the word.

01:08:24.100 --> 01:08:27.680
And that again may
be controversial,

01:08:27.680 --> 01:08:31.940
but that enabled -- that was
only enabled through technology.

01:08:31.940 --> 01:08:35.890
And my career was able to
grow very, very quickly

01:08:35.890 --> 01:08:39.730
when that sort of
paradigm flipped

01:08:39.730 --> 01:08:41.420
because no one was
using the medium.

01:08:41.420 --> 01:08:43.670
So I sort of stepped
into a vacuum.

01:08:43.670 --> 01:08:45.500
And this isn't just about me.

01:08:45.500 --> 01:08:47.480
This is about so
many of the other --

01:08:47.480 --> 01:08:49.990
I will call them thousands
if not millions of creators

01:08:49.990 --> 01:08:51.870
who have been able
to now make a living.

01:08:51.870 --> 01:08:53.620
I mentioned earlier
that there are people

01:08:53.620 --> 01:08:56.100
who will pay 20 thousand
bucks for the little video

01:08:56.100 --> 01:08:57.200
that we made right there.

01:08:57.200 --> 01:08:59.520
Maybe not that one because that
was pretty boring honestly.

01:08:59.520 --> 01:09:03.890
But the point is that
there is a new economy,

01:09:03.890 --> 01:09:06.600
and we are experiencing
seismic shifts

01:09:06.600 --> 01:09:09.810
in how the technology world

01:09:09.810 --> 01:09:12.210
and the creative
world are interacting.

01:09:12.210 --> 01:09:16.530
I think it's, by and large,
up to us to define whether

01:09:16.530 --> 01:09:20.540
that will be positive or not.

01:09:20.540 --> 01:09:22.100
&gt;&gt; Great. So, Jared.

01:09:22.100 --> 01:09:25.030
Your organization is
unique to say the least.

01:09:25.030 --> 01:09:28.480
And I'm wondering why do you
use non-exclusive licenses

01:09:28.480 --> 01:09:30.950
and why do you invite
creators to the table

01:09:30.950 --> 01:09:35.040
to discuss revenue sharing?

01:09:35.040 --> 01:09:41.590
&gt;&gt; So, I think the internet
can be, probably is,

01:09:41.590 --> 01:09:46.590
a very scary place, and when --

01:09:46.590 --> 01:09:49.830
every so often when a social
network you're on, like Facebook

01:09:49.830 --> 01:09:52.370
or Instagram, updates
their terms of service

01:09:52.370 --> 01:09:58.530
and certain elements are
revealed that organizations want

01:09:58.530 --> 01:10:01.660
to make money through
your IP in certain kinds

01:10:01.660 --> 01:10:04.510
of ways, we all freak out.

01:10:04.510 --> 01:10:09.080
We're very transparent
with our --

01:10:09.080 --> 01:10:12.650
with what we're doing
at HITRECORD.

01:10:12.650 --> 01:10:16.420
It's very important to create
a really safe environment

01:10:16.420 --> 01:10:19.770
if you're going to
create art together.

01:10:19.770 --> 01:10:22.380
So we're very clear
and transparent

01:10:22.380 --> 01:10:26.660
with what it is we do and
how it is we make things.

01:10:26.660 --> 01:10:29.650
And that really -- and if
you're going to do that

01:10:29.650 --> 01:10:35.090
and you're going to have that
dialogue, it has to be fair.

01:10:35.090 --> 01:10:39.410
And we're very active
with that dialogue.

01:10:39.410 --> 01:10:43.150
In terms of non-exclusivity,
we want you to be able

01:10:43.150 --> 01:10:49.350
to use your IP to do
whatever you want to do.

01:10:49.350 --> 01:10:52.620
We don't want to own it.

01:10:52.620 --> 01:10:55.650
We don't want to
control your ideas.

01:10:55.650 --> 01:11:01.780
But we are a for-profit
organization so if we can figure

01:11:01.780 --> 01:11:05.000
out a way to make money with
your ideas in combination

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:07.800
with everybody else's ideas,

01:11:07.800 --> 01:11:09.660
there needs to be some
sort of agreement.

01:11:09.660 --> 01:11:11.460
And so we enter into that.

01:11:11.460 --> 01:11:14.410
And when we talk about
profit sharing, we've --

01:11:14.410 --> 01:11:16.780
as Joe mentioned in the
video -- we've paid out --

01:11:16.780 --> 01:11:19.250
at the end of this
year, it'll be closer

01:11:19.250 --> 01:11:21.570
to 2.5 million dollars.

01:11:21.570 --> 01:11:26.740
And when we were thinking of
our terms of service and laying

01:11:26.740 --> 01:11:32.060
out our monetization policy,
we wanted to make it efficient

01:11:32.060 --> 01:11:34.850
and just make a formula
or create an algorithm

01:11:34.850 --> 01:11:38.180
and just say, "All right,
that's how you get paid."

01:11:38.180 --> 01:11:40.230
But it's not -- that's
not how it works.

01:11:40.230 --> 01:11:42.260
Every piece of art is different.

01:11:42.260 --> 01:11:45.110
Every ingredient to that
piece of art is different.

01:11:45.110 --> 01:11:50.120
And how you feel about that
piece of art is different.

01:11:50.120 --> 01:11:56.520
So what we do is every pay
period, we take the money

01:11:56.520 --> 01:11:58.710
that was made for that project.

01:11:58.710 --> 01:12:03.060
We post those profits on the
site for everybody to see,

01:12:03.060 --> 01:12:05.590
and we say, "These are
all of the elements

01:12:05.590 --> 01:12:08.020
that went into this project."

01:12:08.020 --> 01:12:09.460
Whether it's a music video,

01:12:09.460 --> 01:12:11.390
whether it's a television
episode,

01:12:11.390 --> 01:12:15.530
whether it's a TV commercial,
whether it's a vinyl record.

01:12:15.530 --> 01:12:17.630
We say, "These are all the
things that went into it."

01:12:17.630 --> 01:12:23.520
And this is what we think is a
fair split amongst everybody.

01:12:23.520 --> 01:12:27.800
And the community has two weeks

01:12:27.800 --> 01:12:30.630
to have an open dialogue
about that.

01:12:30.630 --> 01:12:32.260
Now, we've been doing
it for six years.

01:12:32.260 --> 01:12:36.500
So there are pretty much --
a lot of the question marks

01:12:36.500 --> 01:12:40.790
and variables as to how this
would work in different cases,

01:12:40.790 --> 01:12:43.230
there's a precedent for it.

01:12:43.230 --> 01:12:47.080
But for two weeks, we
have an open discussion.

01:12:47.080 --> 01:12:48.760
Some people say,
"You forgot me."

01:12:48.760 --> 01:12:50.440
Or, "Maybe I should get more."

01:12:50.440 --> 01:12:54.500
Or, this person may be, "I
want to give mine to this."

01:12:54.500 --> 01:12:56.320
And we have that discussion.

01:12:56.320 --> 01:12:59.190
And at the end of two
weeks, we say, "Okay,

01:12:59.190 --> 01:13:01.010
we take that feedback
into consideration,

01:13:01.010 --> 01:13:02.250
and then we make a decision."

01:13:02.250 --> 01:13:05.450
And what we have found is
that people, of course,

01:13:05.450 --> 01:13:08.280
love getting paid and
recognized for what they do.

01:13:08.280 --> 01:13:14.120
But I should say the attribution
and the credit is almost

01:13:14.120 --> 01:13:17.710
as important, if not more
important, just that people know

01:13:17.710 --> 01:13:20.850
that they got credit for
what their contribution was.

01:13:20.850 --> 01:13:22.130
What's really great --

01:13:22.130 --> 01:13:25.430
and I think there's videos
of Joe signing checks.

01:13:25.430 --> 01:13:30.800
I mean, it's more automated
now, but it is really gratifying

01:13:30.800 --> 01:13:35.240
to have -- to see a stack of
checks go out to thousands

01:13:35.240 --> 01:13:38.180
of artists all over
the world for stuff

01:13:38.180 --> 01:13:40.840
that we've made together
and feeling good

01:13:40.840 --> 01:13:42.590
that everybody feels good.

01:13:42.590 --> 01:13:46.050
Not only about the stuff that
we've made, but about how --

01:13:46.050 --> 01:13:48.810
what they were paid
and how they were paid.

01:13:48.810 --> 01:13:49.920
&gt;&gt; Great, thanks.

01:13:49.920 --> 01:13:54.120
So, Anna, the nature of
Gather is local and intimate.

01:13:54.120 --> 01:13:57.550
And so presumably that affects
the way that you can scale.

01:13:57.550 --> 01:13:59.390
So I'm wondering, how do
you think of it as an asset

01:13:59.390 --> 01:14:00.930
and how is it a limitation?

01:14:00.930 --> 01:14:02.660
&gt;&gt; Yeah, that's such
a good question.

01:14:02.660 --> 01:14:09.220
And I think we are in such
beginning stages of our business

01:14:09.220 --> 01:14:12.640
that it remains to be seen
how that's actually going

01:14:12.640 --> 01:14:13.880
to play out.

01:14:13.880 --> 01:14:17.710
But I do think that first
of all, the localness,

01:14:17.710 --> 01:14:22.620
if you want to call it that,
of Gather is truly an asset

01:14:22.620 --> 01:14:24.480
because it allows people to --

01:14:24.480 --> 01:14:26.950
and I think people
have this compulsion --

01:14:26.950 --> 01:14:30.300
I know in Minnesota this is the
case anyway, to want to dig deep

01:14:30.300 --> 01:14:34.380
into something really
close to home

01:14:34.380 --> 01:14:39.480
that when we feel really
good about spending dollars

01:14:39.480 --> 01:14:43.340
from an artist like two
blocks from our house

01:14:43.340 --> 01:14:46.390
or we feel even better
when we realize

01:14:46.390 --> 01:14:51.110
that our contribution went
to creating a commission

01:14:51.110 --> 01:14:53.470
that would never have happened

01:14:53.470 --> 01:14:56.020
without my small
little contribution

01:14:56.020 --> 01:14:57.990
from the artist in northeast.

01:14:57.990 --> 01:15:03.110
So I think there's something
really gratifying about that.

01:15:03.110 --> 01:15:07.940
I also think that it
helps really create,

01:15:07.940 --> 01:15:11.750
generate an audience
that has the capability

01:15:11.750 --> 01:15:13.870
of transforming individual
artist's lives.

01:15:13.870 --> 01:15:16.520
So that there's truly
a mechanism

01:15:16.520 --> 01:15:20.320
by which the community can
impact the continued development

01:15:20.320 --> 01:15:22.570
of a local arts economy,
which is something

01:15:22.570 --> 01:15:24.500
that we think a lot
about in Minneapolis.

01:15:24.500 --> 01:15:27.680
So I think that that
is an asset,

01:15:27.680 --> 01:15:30.680
and that's really something that
we want to promote and foster.

01:15:30.680 --> 01:15:35.640
I imagine that Gather will begin
to extend, and we already kind

01:15:35.640 --> 01:15:38.600
of do between Minnesota and
Wisconsin, that there's kind

01:15:38.600 --> 01:15:43.150
of an upper Midwestern region
that we'll be really kind

01:15:43.150 --> 01:15:44.680
of focusing on developing.

01:15:44.680 --> 01:15:48.870
And as far as scaling
beyond that, I think there's

01:15:48.870 --> 01:15:52.010
that compulsion exists
in other communities.

01:15:52.010 --> 01:15:54.950
And so the way that we
imagine expansion is

01:15:54.950 --> 01:15:58.770
to actually franchise
in kind of a weird way,

01:15:58.770 --> 01:16:03.880
but to have individual artists
and kind of groups of people

01:16:03.880 --> 01:16:06.890
to curate because I think
curation is really essentially

01:16:06.890 --> 01:16:08.070
to our process as well.

01:16:08.070 --> 01:16:14.870
But to curate a similarly
locally-based version of Gather

01:16:14.870 --> 01:16:16.460
in different corners of the U.S.

01:16:16.460 --> 01:16:18.690
So we're not sure how
that's going to happen.

01:16:18.690 --> 01:16:21.360
We're kind of like trying
to dig deep right now

01:16:21.360 --> 01:16:26.220
into the Minneapolis, St. Paul,
and bigger Minnesota market.

01:16:26.220 --> 01:16:29.780
But I think it has
a lot of potential.

01:16:29.780 --> 01:16:34.910
Like I said, people really
do like supporting local.

01:16:34.910 --> 01:16:39.280
And also being able to kind of
point at something on their wall

01:16:39.280 --> 01:16:41.940
and say, "Not only
is that a cool piece,

01:16:41.940 --> 01:16:43.260
but it's from across town.

01:16:43.260 --> 01:16:46.320
I actually met the
person that made that."

01:16:46.320 --> 01:16:49.130
And there's just like a lot
of warm fuzzies about that.

01:16:49.130 --> 01:16:51.720
So we want to continue
to promote that.

01:16:51.720 --> 01:16:54.590
&gt;&gt; Sure. All right, thanks.

01:16:54.590 --> 01:16:57.710
Chase. CreativeLive enables
revenue stream for creators

01:16:57.710 --> 01:17:01.550
who are also educators by paying
instructors to teach courses.

01:17:01.550 --> 01:17:04.290
So what philosophies do you
have in selecting and working

01:17:04.290 --> 01:17:06.450
with these instructors?

01:17:06.450 --> 01:17:08.110
&gt;&gt; I'll borrow your term.

01:17:08.110 --> 01:17:12.730
Curation. It's absolutely
critical that the people

01:17:12.730 --> 01:17:16.200
that are teaching at
CreativeLive are the best.

01:17:16.200 --> 01:17:18.600
There are many sort
of marketplaces,

01:17:18.600 --> 01:17:21.740
online education marketplaces
-- I don't need to name them.

01:17:21.740 --> 01:17:23.080
The way I describe it, though,

01:17:23.080 --> 01:17:25.560
is they're an inch
deep and a mile wide.

01:17:25.560 --> 01:17:28.570
And they really don't care
who's on their platform.

01:17:28.570 --> 01:17:34.450
It is sort of something that
was by and large created in a --

01:17:34.450 --> 01:17:36.810
I know most of these companies
very intimately and they,

01:17:36.810 --> 01:17:40.610
by and large, were created
by MBA's with business plans

01:17:40.610 --> 01:17:43.050
to scale online education.

01:17:43.050 --> 01:17:48.410
We consider ourselves very,
very focused on creativity.

01:17:48.410 --> 01:17:52.070
Photography, design, video,
music and audio, crafts,

01:17:52.070 --> 01:17:54.300
the maker movement, and the
ability to make a living

01:17:54.300 --> 01:17:55.940
and a life, and all
those things.

01:17:55.940 --> 01:17:58.130
And so for us, we want
to serve a community,

01:17:58.130 --> 01:17:59.900
a community of creators
who are going

01:17:59.900 --> 01:18:02.100
from zero to one or one to ten.

01:18:02.100 --> 01:18:08.350
And in that world, our name, our
brand, the value that we bring

01:18:08.350 --> 01:18:11.240
to our students is all we have.

01:18:11.240 --> 01:18:15.510
And so taking that
lightly would be something

01:18:15.510 --> 01:18:20.650
that I wouldn't advocate as the
founder and CEO, and deciding

01:18:20.650 --> 01:18:22.760
who gets to be the people

01:18:22.760 --> 01:18:26.270
who teach our future
artists is a thing

01:18:26.270 --> 01:18:27.460
that we don't take lightly.

01:18:27.460 --> 01:18:31.820
We take that very, very
seriously because we're trying

01:18:31.820 --> 01:18:36.080
to arm these creators with
the skills that they need

01:18:36.080 --> 01:18:37.270
to go into the future.

01:18:37.270 --> 01:18:40.640
And we're all literally
assembled here on World IP Day

01:18:40.640 --> 01:18:42.830
because the future
is so uncertain

01:18:42.830 --> 01:18:45.790
and we need the stewards
of our future to be people

01:18:45.790 --> 01:18:49.680
who are validated, who are
carefully curated to sort

01:18:49.680 --> 01:18:53.580
of help the rising tide
float all the boats.

01:18:53.580 --> 01:18:56.010
So we're meticulous about it.

01:18:56.010 --> 01:19:00.200
I wouldn't bore you with the
actual details, but it has to do

01:19:00.200 --> 01:19:05.140
with being great at what you do
and also have teaching skills.

01:19:05.140 --> 01:19:06.330
It's no different -- think

01:19:06.330 --> 01:19:09.730
of the best teachers
-- actually do this.

01:19:09.730 --> 01:19:13.020
Think of the best
teachers you ever had.

01:19:13.020 --> 01:19:15.120
They were not the smartest.

01:19:15.120 --> 01:19:20.840
They were part entertaining,
part wise, very much human,

01:19:20.840 --> 01:19:24.030
and those are the people that we
seek to bring on our platform.

01:19:24.030 --> 01:19:25.820
So it's not just the
people with the most papers.

01:19:25.820 --> 01:19:28.010
It's not the people who
have the most experience.

01:19:28.010 --> 01:19:31.800
It's the people who are
great teachers, that connect.

01:19:31.800 --> 01:19:34.660
You like to say that there's a
human being behind the pieces

01:19:34.660 --> 01:19:37.130
of art, and we want
our instructors,

01:19:37.130 --> 01:19:40.130
our experts to be world
class, to be all these things

01:19:40.130 --> 01:19:43.290
and to be able to
connect with a community.

01:19:43.290 --> 01:19:45.530
So we take that very,
very seriously,

01:19:45.530 --> 01:19:47.750
something I'm super proud of.

01:19:47.750 --> 01:19:49.190
&gt;&gt; Great, thanks.

01:19:49.190 --> 01:19:51.050
Jared, you probably
came to your project

01:19:51.050 --> 01:19:53.990
with certain goals
and philosophies.

01:19:53.990 --> 01:19:57.440
Has HITRECORD exceeded
your expectations

01:19:57.440 --> 01:20:01.460
or taught you new things
about the creative process?

01:20:01.460 --> 01:20:01.880
&gt;&gt; Well, yeah.

01:20:01.880 --> 01:20:08.380
I think one of the most
inspiring things about HITRECORD

01:20:08.380 --> 01:20:11.810
for me is that there's
no end to the creativity

01:20:11.810 --> 01:20:15.990
that is contributed every day,
whether that's writing or music

01:20:15.990 --> 01:20:19.770
or animation or --
I mean, stop motion,

01:20:19.770 --> 01:20:22.230
claymation, all sorts of things.

01:20:22.230 --> 01:20:25.670
And what's -- one of the things

01:20:25.670 --> 01:20:31.710
that I've learned is the
more people who have a say

01:20:31.710 --> 01:20:37.150
and the more people who are a
part of the art that we make,

01:20:37.150 --> 01:20:41.270
the richer these stories,
the richer the art is,

01:20:41.270 --> 01:20:43.460
the more perspectives.

01:20:43.460 --> 01:20:48.690
And we just hear stories that
we just never would have written

01:20:48.690 --> 01:20:51.720
ourselves because
we just didn't --

01:20:51.720 --> 01:20:55.550
we don't have that experience.

01:20:55.550 --> 01:20:58.480
When we were doing the first
season of our television show,

01:20:58.480 --> 01:21:01.620
the first episode of our
show was regarding --

01:21:01.620 --> 01:21:04.230
we had art and ideas and --

01:21:04.230 --> 01:21:06.440
about regarding a
different theme.

01:21:06.440 --> 01:21:08.890
Each episode is regarding
a different theme.

01:21:08.890 --> 01:21:11.460
And the first episode was
regarding the number one.

01:21:11.460 --> 01:21:16.040
And we had a -- we had a -- we
put out a call to action to say,

01:21:16.040 --> 01:21:19.850
"Tell us about your -- tell
us your stories regarding your

01:21:19.850 --> 01:21:20.660
first time."

01:21:20.660 --> 01:21:22.340
And that was your first
time doing anything.

01:21:22.340 --> 01:21:26.190
So people wrote all sorts of
stories, contributed stories,

01:21:26.190 --> 01:21:29.930
and one girl wrote a
story about the first time

01:21:29.930 --> 01:21:33.390
that she saw the stars
when she was 16 years old.

01:21:33.390 --> 01:21:35.020
She has a rare eye disorder

01:21:35.020 --> 01:21:38.070
where she can't see
pinpoints of light.

01:21:38.070 --> 01:21:44.480
And when she was 16, her Dad
bought her night vision goggles

01:21:44.480 --> 01:21:47.190
to allow her to see the
stars for the first time.

01:21:47.190 --> 01:21:50.890
And that's just a story that
we never would have heard

01:21:50.890 --> 01:21:53.090
if we just hired
a bunch of writers

01:21:53.090 --> 01:21:55.390
in Hollywood in a writer's room.

01:21:55.390 --> 01:22:01.300
But when you have such a
huge community of artists

01:22:01.300 --> 01:22:04.560
that are contributing
ideas to these stories,

01:22:04.560 --> 01:22:09.690
I think that's the most
surprising thing is every

01:22:09.690 --> 01:22:12.230
collaboration that we
do is you never know --

01:22:12.230 --> 01:22:14.350
we always have to throw caution
to the wind whenever we --

01:22:14.350 --> 01:22:17.280
and can't plan too much
about where we're going to go

01:22:17.280 --> 01:22:19.330
with a certain project
because we go

01:22:19.330 --> 01:22:21.520
where the community wants to go.

01:22:21.520 --> 01:22:25.490
It's where we --
where's the story going?

01:22:25.490 --> 01:22:29.740
And I think that's -- again, one
of the most surprising things

01:22:29.740 --> 01:22:36.170
and the thing that I
love about creating art

01:22:36.170 --> 01:22:38.930
in a digital space is that
you just have the scale

01:22:38.930 --> 01:22:42.770
of people with different ideas.

01:22:42.770 --> 01:22:46.040
&gt;&gt; That was the last question?

01:22:46.040 --> 01:22:48.060
[ Inaudible ]

01:22:48.060 --> 01:22:48.920
Okay. All right.

01:22:48.920 --> 01:22:53.270
Well, I guess we're
to the last question.

01:22:53.270 --> 01:22:58.510
Okay. Can each of you briefly
state what do you think the

01:22:58.510 --> 01:22:59.440
future holds?

01:22:59.440 --> 01:23:03.050
And let's start with Jared.

01:23:03.050 --> 01:23:04.640
&gt;&gt; Future.

01:23:04.640 --> 01:23:05.170
&gt;&gt; Future holds.

01:23:05.170 --> 01:23:08.640
Specifically, I imagine,
with regards to art making

01:23:08.640 --> 01:23:10.960
and the digital space
and copyright.

01:23:10.960 --> 01:23:13.690
I think -- first
of all, I think --

01:23:13.690 --> 01:23:17.490
and one of the things I was
thinking about on the plane ride

01:23:17.490 --> 01:23:23.920
over here was just the fact
that World IP Day exists

01:23:23.920 --> 01:23:27.160
and people are learning
more about what that means

01:23:27.160 --> 01:23:30.090
and educating artists
as to the value

01:23:30.090 --> 01:23:35.390
of their contribution
is a huge step forward

01:23:35.390 --> 01:23:41.720
in us not only understanding
what the value of our ideas

01:23:41.720 --> 01:23:44.620
in art is but what
we can do about it.

01:23:44.620 --> 01:23:48.380
And so I'm -- I think it's
going to be an evolution.

01:23:48.380 --> 01:23:52.920
I think there's always going
to be a push and pull and --

01:23:52.920 --> 01:24:00.280
but I'm extremely optimistic
just -- and I said it earlier,

01:24:00.280 --> 01:24:05.860
but meeting everybody here who
is so passionate about copyright

01:24:05.860 --> 01:24:10.930
and figuring things
out with artists,

01:24:10.930 --> 01:24:14.780
I think it's a challenging time,
but it's a really inspiring

01:24:14.780 --> 01:24:18.380
and exciting time to
be a part of this.

01:24:18.380 --> 01:24:20.940
There's -- I think it's --

01:24:20.940 --> 01:24:25.920
what a pressing issue and
what an exciting time to help

01:24:25.920 --> 01:24:29.130
to start figuring
these things out.

01:24:29.130 --> 01:24:29.970
&gt;&gt; Excellent.

01:24:29.970 --> 01:24:31.460
Anna?

01:24:31.460 --> 01:24:34.270
&gt;&gt; That is such an
amazing question.

01:24:34.270 --> 01:24:35.350
&gt;&gt; No wrong answers.

01:24:35.350 --> 01:24:36.330
&gt;&gt; Yeah, no.

01:24:36.330 --> 01:24:37.480
It's true.

01:24:37.480 --> 01:24:41.470
I think about this
a lot actually just

01:24:41.470 --> 01:24:45.610
from the perspective of
the other work that I do,

01:24:45.610 --> 01:24:47.250
which is to help artists grow

01:24:47.250 --> 01:24:49.330
in their own professional
development

01:24:49.330 --> 01:24:52.850
and grow their businesses and
grow their living and a life --

01:24:52.850 --> 01:24:55.320
that's such a wonderful slogan.

01:24:55.320 --> 01:24:58.980
That's what we work really
hard to do at Springboard.

01:24:58.980 --> 01:25:05.890
And I think there's this
really interesting tension

01:25:05.890 --> 01:25:09.650
between collaboration -- this
is a word that I think all

01:25:09.650 --> 01:25:14.710
of us talk about -- and then
also having an individual voice.

01:25:14.710 --> 01:25:22.390
And I think that something in
the future will present a "yes,

01:25:22.390 --> 01:25:27.540
and" solution to this
tension in such a way

01:25:27.540 --> 01:25:32.090
where our human species,
the creativity that happens

01:25:32.090 --> 01:25:35.800
when human beings get
together to make art work

01:25:35.800 --> 01:25:38.070
and to push our culture forward,

01:25:38.070 --> 01:25:40.620
which is truly the most
inspirational thing I can

01:25:40.620 --> 01:25:42.290
think of.

01:25:42.290 --> 01:25:45.370
When that can happen
and also acknowledge all

01:25:45.370 --> 01:25:48.680
of the individual voices that
went into that happening,

01:25:48.680 --> 01:25:53.100
and I'm so inspired by all of
the efforts that everyone here

01:25:53.100 --> 01:25:56.500
on the stage are
making to do that,

01:25:56.500 --> 01:26:00.230
so I think that is an optimistic
what I think will happen

01:26:00.230 --> 01:26:04.690
in the future for the arts and
for artists is this, again,

01:26:04.690 --> 01:26:09.330
realization of the movement
forward as a collective

01:26:09.330 --> 01:26:12.060
and also the individual
voice being recognized.

01:26:12.060 --> 01:26:12.970
&gt;&gt; Great, great.

01:26:12.970 --> 01:26:14.270
Chase, the future?

01:26:14.270 --> 01:26:18.280
&gt;&gt; I'm inspired by
my stage mates here.

01:26:18.280 --> 01:26:22.740
I think Jared, you said it well
with -- it's an exciting time.

01:26:22.740 --> 01:26:24.610
We used the word tension
a lot last night as well.

01:26:24.610 --> 01:26:26.530
I think it is the most
exciting time in the history

01:26:26.530 --> 01:26:28.000
of the world to be a creator.

01:26:28.000 --> 01:26:32.150
I think there is a tension
around sort of preserving

01:26:32.150 --> 01:26:34.920
that in a way that
maintains sustenance

01:26:34.920 --> 01:26:37.370
for the people who create.

01:26:37.370 --> 01:26:40.450
As the world sort of
commodifies so many things

01:26:40.450 --> 01:26:43.610
and goods are being made
cheaper and cheaper all the time

01:26:43.610 --> 01:26:48.380
and in many ways, intellectual
property is becoming

01:26:48.380 --> 01:26:55.120
commoditized, how do we keep
this from being a problem?

01:26:55.120 --> 01:26:59.300
To me, that is a very, very
-- it is the responsibility --

01:26:59.300 --> 01:27:04.530
I'm honored to hear that
people love World IP Day.

01:27:04.530 --> 01:27:07.260
That you are out there thinking
about that on a daily basis.

01:27:07.260 --> 01:27:10.220
I believe deeply that this
is very much a packaging

01:27:10.220 --> 01:27:13.120
and an access challenge.

01:27:13.120 --> 01:27:14.720
The packaging --

01:27:14.720 --> 01:27:17.470
I have litigated against
a publicly traded company.

01:27:17.470 --> 01:27:19.880
I want to say thanks to Gene
Mopsik from the ASMP for helping

01:27:19.880 --> 01:27:21.760
to support it, five years,

01:27:21.760 --> 01:27:24.520
hundreds of thousands
of dollars in costs.

01:27:24.520 --> 01:27:27.230
I had a -- it was against
-- I'll just say it,

01:27:27.230 --> 01:27:29.840
it was against K2,
a ski manufacturer.

01:27:29.840 --> 01:27:31.890
It's a well-documented case.

01:27:31.890 --> 01:27:33.860
It was more than
150 infringements.

01:27:33.860 --> 01:27:35.040
Cost me five years of my life.

01:27:35.040 --> 01:27:37.820
I had to testify in
federal court for three days

01:27:37.820 --> 01:27:40.770
by an attorney that was making
12 hundred dollars an hour

01:27:40.770 --> 01:27:41.770
to be there.

01:27:41.770 --> 01:27:46.940
And that -- we won that case and
had to appeal our own victory

01:27:46.940 --> 01:27:49.930
because the judgment was
written in such a way

01:27:49.930 --> 01:27:51.620
that it was bad for artists.

01:27:51.620 --> 01:27:53.840
So we appealed that, and it
went to the Ninth Circuit Court

01:27:53.840 --> 01:27:56.450
of Appeals where we
won that as well.

01:27:56.450 --> 01:27:59.300
And I loved the opening
remarks because if you think

01:27:59.300 --> 01:28:03.050
that cost me hundreds of
thousands of dollars in order

01:28:03.050 --> 01:28:05.920
to do that, and what
K2, the reason --

01:28:05.920 --> 01:28:09.950
I had a voice message that
accidentally was removed

01:28:09.950 --> 01:28:13.090
at some point from my message
because it was saved so long

01:28:13.090 --> 01:28:16.380
of the vice president saying
really unpleasant things

01:28:16.380 --> 01:28:19.730
to me like, "You don't know
who you're f-- - - - g with."

01:28:19.730 --> 01:28:23.200
And if that is the plight
of artists going forward,

01:28:23.200 --> 01:28:26.080
we're in a real bad spot.

01:28:26.080 --> 01:28:29.560
If the people in this room
can usurp that mentality

01:28:29.560 --> 01:28:33.320
and if we can through a
packaging exercise of making --

01:28:33.320 --> 01:28:36.540
World IP Day is a great
step, but let's make it sexy

01:28:36.540 --> 01:28:39.650
to understand that there
is value in our creators.

01:28:39.650 --> 01:28:43.530
Let's create access to that
information because access

01:28:43.530 --> 01:28:46.440
to information is
really what helps sort

01:28:46.440 --> 01:28:49.020
of the tide rise
with all the boats.

01:28:49.020 --> 01:28:53.060
By and large, I find that most
of my peers who are struggling

01:28:53.060 --> 01:28:55.300
to make a living and a life is

01:28:55.300 --> 01:28:58.370
because they either
have not chosen to

01:28:58.370 --> 01:29:00.170
or they don't have
an understanding

01:29:00.170 --> 01:29:02.180
of access to that information.

01:29:02.180 --> 01:29:06.150
So my ask is that that
is what the committees,

01:29:06.150 --> 01:29:11.630
the Copyright Office,
Congress consider as their sort

01:29:11.630 --> 01:29:14.740
of their future,
their future moves.

01:29:14.740 --> 01:29:17.610
It's an incredibly
exciting time.

01:29:17.610 --> 01:29:19.050
It's a little bit dangerous,

01:29:19.050 --> 01:29:22.540
and I believe our
fate is in good hands.

01:29:22.540 --> 01:29:25.050
Good shall persevere.

01:29:26.510 --> 01:29:30.330
[ Inaudible ]

01:29:30.330 --> 01:29:32.700
&gt;&gt; All right, so we're going
to open it up to the audience

01:29:32.700 --> 01:29:34.150
if anybody has any questions.

01:29:34.150 --> 01:29:35.640
I believe there are microphones,

01:29:35.640 --> 01:29:38.360
so if you could wait
for the mic.

01:29:38.360 --> 01:29:39.970
Don't be shy.

01:29:41.600 --> 01:29:43.990
&gt;&gt; Come on, you guys.

01:29:43.990 --> 01:29:47.430
We came all the way across
the country for this.

01:29:47.430 --> 01:29:49.260
&gt;&gt; Now's your chance.

01:29:51.060 --> 01:29:55.200
There's a gift for the
first person who asks.

01:29:55.200 --> 01:29:59.130
&gt;&gt; Hi. My name is
[inaudible], the US editor

01:29:59.130 --> 01:30:02.030
for a magazine called
Music Week,

01:30:02.030 --> 01:30:03.710
and I cover copyright issues.

01:30:03.710 --> 01:30:04.830
Oh, thank you for the gift.

01:30:04.830 --> 01:30:05.800
That's lovely.

01:30:05.800 --> 01:30:07.210
I didn't know there was one.

01:30:07.210 --> 01:30:08.230
I thought you were just --

01:30:08.230 --> 01:30:11.180
The Copyright Alliance
serves a purpose --

01:30:11.180 --> 01:30:15.900
there's one thing in the videos
and also in a couple of things

01:30:15.900 --> 01:30:18.440
that you said about
information wants to be free.

01:30:18.440 --> 01:30:21.800
Isn't there a problem when
every time you mention the work

01:30:21.800 --> 01:30:26.920
of art, actually it becomes
information, i.e. one and zero.

01:30:26.920 --> 01:30:31.490
And the semantics are important
in a sense that whenever --

01:30:31.490 --> 01:30:33.390
and it really used to upset me

01:30:33.390 --> 01:30:35.040
when I think information
wants to be free.

01:30:35.040 --> 01:30:36.690
Therefore, we can access music.

01:30:36.690 --> 01:30:39.460
We can access photography,
etc. These are not --

01:30:39.460 --> 01:30:40.700
this is not information.

01:30:40.700 --> 01:30:42.240
These are works of art.

01:30:42.240 --> 01:30:46.060
So shouldn't we start by
instead of saying information,

01:30:46.060 --> 01:30:49.590
saying that these are works of
art and that will help everyone

01:30:49.590 --> 01:30:51.550
to actually understand
what it is?

01:30:51.550 --> 01:30:53.800
&gt;&gt; To be clear, I was talking
about information in terms

01:30:53.800 --> 01:30:55.990
of access to the information
about art, not actually

01:30:55.990 --> 01:30:57.440
about art in and of itself.

01:30:57.440 --> 01:31:01.010
But I understand very,
very deeply your --

01:31:01.010 --> 01:31:02.920
how the challenge exists there.

01:31:02.920 --> 01:31:05.280
Again, I dropped out of a
Ph.D. in the Philosophy of Art

01:31:05.280 --> 01:31:10.200
so this is really, really
an interesting area for me.

01:31:10.200 --> 01:31:13.150
The -- I guess I
don't want to pretend

01:31:13.150 --> 01:31:14.250
that it's not complicated.

01:31:14.250 --> 01:31:16.700
And if we've had some of
the brightest thinkers

01:31:16.700 --> 01:31:21.140
of our times struggling
in politics,

01:31:21.140 --> 01:31:24.270
in the Copyright Office, in our
government and governments all

01:31:24.270 --> 01:31:26.550
over the world -- if
there's a real challenge

01:31:26.550 --> 01:31:28.900
to overcoming these problems,
I don't think one of us

01:31:28.900 --> 01:31:30.710
from the stage is
going to answer it.

01:31:30.710 --> 01:31:32.820
But let's actually acknowledge

01:31:32.820 --> 01:31:36.760
that what you've said
is the central problem.

01:31:36.760 --> 01:31:41.160
There really is a gap between
saying well, this is just a mess

01:31:41.160 --> 01:31:44.000
and what do we do about
it, and saying actually,

01:31:44.000 --> 01:31:45.400
let's identify the problem.

01:31:45.400 --> 01:31:48.300
The problem is that is
one very precise problem

01:31:48.300 --> 01:31:50.440
that we need to try and solve.

01:31:50.440 --> 01:31:54.340
And to say that it's just
too big for us to tackle.

01:31:54.340 --> 01:31:56.510
We have a history
in this country.

01:31:56.510 --> 01:31:58.240
Our law was created over time.

01:31:58.240 --> 01:32:00.330
We didn't just walk out
and say this is the law.

01:32:00.330 --> 01:32:03.490
I think I know just a little
bit about the philosophy of law,

01:32:03.490 --> 01:32:07.760
and it was created over time,
and it continues to evolve.

01:32:07.760 --> 01:32:08.900
We have to put a
stake in the ground

01:32:08.900 --> 01:32:10.930
and saying these are a couple
of the central challenges

01:32:10.930 --> 01:32:11.920
that we're going
to try and solve.

01:32:11.920 --> 01:32:14.000
And if we don't put
a pin in those things

01:32:14.000 --> 01:32:15.740
and start working
toward that solution,

01:32:15.740 --> 01:32:16.800
we certainly will
never get there.

01:32:16.800 --> 01:32:17.520
You know that saying?

01:32:17.520 --> 01:32:18.680
If you don't have a
map, you're not going

01:32:18.680 --> 01:32:20.140
to get where you're going.

01:32:20.140 --> 01:32:21.710
You can't just walk
in the woods.

01:32:21.710 --> 01:32:24.210
Or even a broken clock
is right twice a day,

01:32:24.210 --> 01:32:25.500
whatever that saying is.

01:32:25.500 --> 01:32:27.400
We need to identify the problem.

01:32:27.400 --> 01:32:29.480
Keep going.

01:32:29.480 --> 01:32:31.430
Come on, you guys.

01:32:31.430 --> 01:32:34.470
&gt;&gt; To build upon what you
were saying, there is a --

01:32:34.470 --> 01:32:35.580
I think there is a culture

01:32:35.580 --> 01:32:39.580
because that is the
central problem.

01:32:39.580 --> 01:32:44.790
Well, I'll just share
this music or I have no --

01:32:44.790 --> 01:32:50.490
people might be predisposed to
be fine with just taking music

01:32:50.490 --> 01:32:55.470
or in essence, stealing music,
because that's just the culture

01:32:55.470 --> 01:32:56.390
that we're now living in.

01:32:56.390 --> 01:32:58.500
And I think that
you said it right.

01:32:58.500 --> 01:33:02.490
All right, now I think it's
really raising our hands

01:33:02.490 --> 01:33:04.500
and saying actually
this, understanding

01:33:04.500 --> 01:33:07.170
that this is a problem,
understanding that this way

01:33:07.170 --> 01:33:10.870
of thinking shouldn't be the way
of thinking and then figuring

01:33:10.870 --> 01:33:13.190
out well, how do
we deal with this?

01:33:13.190 --> 01:33:16.710
But it is -- I do think that
we are living in a culture

01:33:16.710 --> 01:33:20.280
where I think there
are a lot of people

01:33:20.280 --> 01:33:23.380
who just think it's okay
because it's so easy.

01:33:23.380 --> 01:33:27.960
How could something
so easy not be okay?

01:33:27.960 --> 01:33:34.360
So it's identifying that problem
and then figuring it out.

01:33:34.360 --> 01:33:37.510
&gt;&gt; And also I think identifying

01:33:37.510 --> 01:33:39.490
where there are solutions
already embedded

01:33:39.490 --> 01:33:44.860
into that question and the
problem because what I find is

01:33:44.860 --> 01:33:48.170
that artists don't --
smaller artists, anyway,

01:33:48.170 --> 01:33:52.250
don't tend to have the
problem of too much exposure.

01:33:52.250 --> 01:33:56.850
In fact, they really need
more exposure and that idea

01:33:56.850 --> 01:34:00.000
of turning what they
do into information

01:34:00.000 --> 01:34:03.340
that can be widely distributed
is often times the thing

01:34:03.340 --> 01:34:06.060
that gives them the
living and the life

01:34:06.060 --> 01:34:09.380
that they can then build upon.

01:34:09.380 --> 01:34:11.650
And so, yeah, I think there's --

01:34:11.650 --> 01:34:15.290
I'm going to use the word
tension again because it --

01:34:15.290 --> 01:34:19.460
certainly -- maybe it's the
two sides of the same coin

01:34:19.460 --> 01:34:23.230
that there is the asset
to information going

01:34:23.230 --> 01:34:26.290
out to the masses and then
there's also what we have

01:34:26.290 --> 01:34:29.920
to do is protect that too.

01:34:29.920 --> 01:34:30.820
Yeah.

01:34:30.820 --> 01:34:36.290
&gt;&gt; Hi. How would your
company protect --

01:34:36.290 --> 01:34:45.290
okay, say if I was to submit
something to your company,

01:34:45.290 --> 01:34:50.330
a picture, and how would
you protect that from those

01:34:50.330 --> 01:34:54.130
who are trying to make a
income, a passive income?

01:34:54.130 --> 01:35:00.400
Say Amazon has a way where you
can copyright somebody's work.

01:35:00.400 --> 01:35:05.620
With HITRECORD, how would you
protect the work that I submit?

01:35:05.620 --> 01:35:10.260
&gt;&gt; If I'm understanding your --
I don't know the Amazon service

01:35:10.260 --> 01:35:11.670
that you're referencing --

01:35:11.670 --> 01:35:14.710
if I'm to understand
your question correctly.

01:35:14.710 --> 01:35:21.530
If you were to upload a
picture and somebody else were

01:35:21.530 --> 01:35:25.140
to download it and try to
make money off of it outside

01:35:25.140 --> 01:35:30.660
of the website, actually we --
it gets back to the question

01:35:30.660 --> 01:35:32.770
about non-exclusivity.

01:35:32.770 --> 01:35:34.710
We don't represent --

01:35:34.710 --> 01:35:38.650
if you were to do
that and it happens --

01:35:38.650 --> 01:35:41.660
I shouldn't say that
it happens --

01:35:41.660 --> 01:35:46.220
I'm not aware of a case where
somebody would download a photo

01:35:46.220 --> 01:35:49.680
and make money, but I
know that there are cases

01:35:49.680 --> 01:35:53.210
where people would
download art off of our site

01:35:53.210 --> 01:35:56.830
and perhaps put it on
Tumblr or on Facebook

01:35:56.830 --> 01:35:59.880
and perhaps there's a
monetization stream that way.

01:35:59.880 --> 01:36:04.460
But we don't represent
the artists for protection

01:36:04.460 --> 01:36:05.440
against that sort of thing.

01:36:05.440 --> 01:36:10.230
And if we did, we would then
require the exclusive rights

01:36:10.230 --> 01:36:13.130
to your IP because then
we can represent you.

01:36:13.130 --> 01:36:15.190
There is an infrastructure
for us to do that.

01:36:15.190 --> 01:36:22.010
We essentially have a
license for us to work with

01:36:22.010 --> 01:36:25.790
and to monetize along
with other people's art.

01:36:25.790 --> 01:36:32.970
So I guess the short
answer is that could happen.

01:36:32.970 --> 01:36:38.310
That's for the artist
to represent themselves.

01:36:38.310 --> 01:36:43.940
That is to say when people make
us aware that things are going

01:36:43.940 --> 01:36:48.380
on with either one
member or a combination --

01:36:48.380 --> 01:36:50.960
if somebody takes your
photo and combines it

01:36:50.960 --> 01:36:54.410
with another member's photo and
tries to do something with it,

01:36:54.410 --> 01:37:01.160
we do make best efforts
to try to make it right.

01:37:01.160 --> 01:37:04.380
But at the end of the day,
we don't have the authority

01:37:04.380 --> 01:37:06.340
to speak on behalf
of the artists

01:37:06.340 --> 01:37:08.770
because we don't have
that kind of license.

01:37:08.770 --> 01:37:14.280
&gt;&gt; I think we have to end.

01:37:14.280 --> 01:37:15.600
Sorry.

01:37:15.600 --> 01:37:16.340
&gt;&gt; Okay.

01:37:16.340 --> 01:37:19.150
&gt;&gt; They'll be here briefly, I
think, after the event if you'd

01:37:19.150 --> 01:37:20.390
like to talk to them
a little bit.

01:37:20.390 --> 01:37:24.620
But would you please help me
thank them for being here today?

01:37:26.510 --> 01:37:33.090
[ Applause ]

01:37:33.090 --> 01:37:34.530
As Register, I'll
take the liberty

01:37:34.530 --> 01:37:36.470
of offering a few
closing remarks.

01:37:36.470 --> 01:37:39.470
Just summarizing
what I just heard.

01:37:39.470 --> 01:37:40.860
Obviously, being an artist

01:37:40.860 --> 01:37:44.570
from what you can tell is an
extremely disciplined craft

01:37:44.570 --> 01:37:47.110
and a lifetime craft at that.

01:37:47.110 --> 01:37:50.880
I agree wholeheartedly with
Chase and his observation

01:37:50.880 --> 01:37:53.240
that you should not, if
you're an artist listening

01:37:53.240 --> 01:37:57.290
to this today or will listen
to it later on our website --

01:37:57.290 --> 01:37:59.770
don't underestimate
participation

01:37:59.770 --> 01:38:01.340
from our nation's artists

01:38:01.340 --> 01:38:04.040
in the copyright debates
going on currently.

01:38:04.040 --> 01:38:07.040
It would be illogical
to have a copyright act

01:38:07.040 --> 01:38:11.540
that does not protect and
support our creative voices.

01:38:11.540 --> 01:38:14.470
We're doing our best in
the Copyright Office.

01:38:14.470 --> 01:38:15.780
There are many organizations

01:38:15.780 --> 01:38:17.940
that obviously agree
with that principle.

01:38:17.940 --> 01:38:21.400
Certainly, Congress does, but
they need to hear from you.

01:38:21.400 --> 01:38:26.440
I'm tempted to provide the
recommendation to Congress

01:38:26.440 --> 01:38:29.760
that they should take
Jared's business model

01:38:29.760 --> 01:38:34.980
of giving everybody two weeks
to weigh in on any proposal

01:38:34.980 --> 01:38:38.310
that comes off the Hill, and
then they'll make a decision.

01:38:38.310 --> 01:38:39.540
I'm not sure it'll go that way.

01:38:39.540 --> 01:38:43.020
So instead, I'll end with Anna's
observation that of course,

01:38:43.020 --> 01:38:45.880
even in the copyright
debate, there is a tension

01:38:45.880 --> 01:38:49.730
between expressing one's
individual goals or perspective

01:38:49.730 --> 01:38:51.630
and then collaborating
with others.

01:38:51.630 --> 01:38:55.810
And of course, we have
to have both so here's

01:38:55.810 --> 01:38:59.290
to working together for the
next great Copyright Act.

01:38:59.290 --> 01:39:03.680
Thanks.

